it was eighty eights year in 88 when 
the little farm town with the numerical name found its moment in the 
spotlight as calendars flipped to 8888 
but once aug 9 dawned eighty eight got back to the everyday 
life of 88 and as in thousands of small towns from coast to 
coast 1988 was a year for drought george bush and the timeless 
rhythms of rural america 
eighty eight has neat houses a grocery a tire company and two 
churches stretching about a mile along a twolane highway its 200 
residents have no local government no school not even a traffic 
light nothing in short that would be likely to attract attention 
but for a few heady days in august when the television networks 
and newspapers and magazines were dispatching reporters and 
photographers and thousands of tourists were trooping to town it 
seemed the whole world was peeking in on eighty eight 
that was a right exciting thing for this little area said 
david dickerson whose familys lumber mill is the largest local 
employer 
it was also a right unlikely thing 
local residents welcomed all comers with an 88 celebration on 
aug 7 and 8 they put on a parade with an 88yearold grand marshal 
and cut a cake 8 feet 8 inches long 
they crowded in front of rose mary mcphersons 88 market and 
shouted good morning america for abctv 
they staged the wedding of the century for a wyoming couple tom 
accardo and deborah muhlbeier at 808 pm on aug 8 
twentysix thousand pieces of mail got the 8888 postmark 
letters still arrive at the closetsize post office in one corner 
of the grocery but for the most part everything is just real 
quiet around here said donnie sue bacon the postmistress id 
say in a week everything got back pretty much to normal 
that is to say eighty eight got back to dairy and tobacco 
farming conservative politics and lunchhour crowds at the 88 
market where ms mcpherson still serves up hot meals or cold cuts 
to the dickerson lumber co gang and other regulars 
it remains a pleasant unpretentious community 
people still eat bologna sandwiches said dickerson i know 
i do 
before and after the tv cameras came and went eighty eight 
mirrored rural america 
in the spring crops were planted and herds were turned out and 
folks in surrounding barren county kentuckys no 1 dairy producer 
looked toward summer 
but the rains stopped the first of june pastures dried up and 
hay that had been stored for winter feeding had to be hauled out 
months early 
in the fall hopes rose with the excellence of the burley tobacco 
crop 
at the polls eighty eight belied its mostly democratic 
registration and helped elect george bush president it also sided 
with voters statewide in approving a constitutional amendment to 
allow a lottery although barren county as a whole voted it down 
deep in july arnold young accustomed to gambles throughout a 
lifetime of farming had to take another 
as a crippling drought dragged on and his cattle ate the hay he 
had planned to feed them in october young had to decide whether to 
follow some of his neighbors and dump his 57 head of dairy and beef 
cattle on the market 
i was beginning to think about it said young 51 but i 
didnt 
the gamble paid off 
the rains returned by the end of july early enough to coax 
another crop of hay from the ground and to get his burley a 
dryweather crop anyway off to a good start 
this year the tobacco crop has turned out a whole lot better 
said young who was in a decidely celebratory mood when he helped 
park cars at the 88 celebration 
i thought it was nice we got a whole lot of recognition he 
said it wont happen for another 100 years i dont think ill be 
parking cars at that one 
forty years ago voters in eighty eight were chronicled by 
ripleys believe it or not when they split in the presidential 
election 88 votes for president harry truman 88 votes for 
republican thomas dewey 
this year the eighty eight precinct cast 88 votes for larry 
freas a democrat from neighboring simpson county in a race for an 
open state senate seat 
democrats hold a 32 registration edge but republican walter 
baker from glasgow the barren county seat got 231 votes here and 
won the election districtwide 
nor was dickerson daunted by the democrats numbers as he lobbied 
locally for the gop ticket of bush and dan quayle which got 216 
votes to 147 for the democratic ticket of michael dukakis and lloyd 
bentsen 
its still a rural precinct and the best way to campaign for 
any candidate is just word of mouth dickerson said you have to 
do a selling job it was particularly easy this year 
