<TEXT>
it was a meager year for musicals but a 
halfdozen deserving new plays and several old ones managed to make 
it to new york and flourish during 1988 
the phantom of the opera was the years biggest hit and its 
best musical deservedly so andrew lloyd webber produced his most 
accomplished score to date lush romantic and sweeping music that 
perfectly captured gaston lerouxs passionate tale of love denied 
michael crawford was a heartstopping and heartbreaking phantom 
harold princes direction was impeccable and maria bjornson 
provided some eyepopping costumes and scenery 
but after phantom which opened in january nothing else 
excited the musical theater for the rest of the year there were 
minor american musicals like the shortlived mail and the two 
oneact musicals about love operating under the title romance 
romance 
the inevitable turkeys also took to the stage particularly two 
british gobblers carrie and chess 
carrie in particular signaled that the british musical 
domination of broadway was over the show was an 8 million 
disaster broadways most expensive flop it was based on the 
stephen king horror novel about a dumpy awkward teenage girl with 
telekinetic powers betty buckley and 16yearold linzi hateley in 
the title role sang their hearts out but nothing could save this 
dud 
new york had better luck with plays particularly new works by 
american authors topping the list and also taking the tony award 
as best play was m butterfly david henry hwangs brilliant 
recreation of a spy scandal and love affair involving a french 
diplomat and a chinese opera singer who turns out to be a man david 
dukes now plays the diplomat and gives such a compelling 
ontheedge performance that the play seems even better than when it 
first opened last march 
other notable new works by established playwrights included joe 
turners come and gone august wilsons story of the search for 
identity among the children of slaves athol fugards the road to 
mecca a tale of one womans determination to remain independent 
speedtheplow david mamets scathing look at hollywood greed 
and glory and the cocktail hour ar gurneys comic 
examination of upperclass generational conflict 
lesserknown playwrights also had success offbroadways 
reckless by craig lucas was a biting black comedy about a 
womans escape from her family after her husband announces he plans 
to have her killed on christmas eve 
richard greenbergs eastern standard offered another 
fascinating evening it opens on broadway jan 5 direct from 
offbroadways manhattan theater club the play follows several 
yuppies as they try to grow up in new york during the late 1980s 
its a witty compassionate play about the most disliked group in 
america 
several actors gave memorable performances this year 
among the best bd wong whose gender switch in m 
butterfly was nothing less than astonishing robin bartlett the 
distraught wife in reckless yvonne bryceland the feisty 
independent sculptor in the road to mecca ron silver oozing an 
insincere charm as a smarmy wouldbe hollywood producer in 
speedtheplow and nancy marchand as a diplomatic and wise wasp 
matriarch in the cocktail hour 
but there were other performances that some actors might want to 
erase from their playbill biographies al pacino martin sheen and 
edward herrmann massacring julius caesar in more ways than one 
madonna sleepwalking through her role in speedtheplow and 
mariette hartley coming to grief as a griefstricken queen in 
shakespeares rarely produced king john 
most underrated performance sarah brightman in the phantom of 
the opera sure she isnt sarah bernhardt but the woman has a 
glorious pristine voice that would be terrific to hear in some 
classic musical comedy by rodgers and hart gershwin or porter and 
lloyd webber wrote the role of christine in phantom for her if 
theres any doubt listen to the singers who have followed her in 
the new york cast not even close 
most overrated performances four of the five performers in the 
revival of aint misbehavin the show should have been called 
are misbehavin considering the extra histrionics vocal and 
otherwise by nell carter ken page armelia mcqueen and charlaine 
woodard only andre de shields managed to rein in the theatrics 
the year produced three exceptional revivals peter brooks spare 
but satisfying version of chekhovs the cherry orchard done by 
the brooklyn academy of music at brooklyns majestic theater sean 
ocaseys juno and the paycock in an atmospheric production 
from the gate theater in dublin and the lincoln center theaters 
dark brooding version of thornton wilders our town 
not hitting the mark was the years most anticipated revival 
samuel becketts waiting for godot starring steve martin and 
robin williams and directed by mike nichols at lincoln center the 
ticket demand was enormous most people including some subscribers 
to the lincoln center theater couldnt get in but what they missed 
was more postmodern burlesque than beckett 
</TEXT>
