<TEXT>
international business machines corp is reducing 
its role in the telecommunications equipment business by selling 
part of its moneylosing rolm operation to west germanys siemens ag 
and putting the rest of rolm into a joint venture with siemens 
the deal announced tuesday marks another chapter in ibms mixed 
success with rolm a freewheeling silicon valley company that the 
computer giant bought four years ago for an estimated 15 billion 
to help it link computers through phone switches 
rolm is believed to have lost hundreds of millions of dollars in 
recent years but has grown into the nations biggest seller of 
office phone switches which route calls within buildings under 
ibms ownership 
the purchase would make siemens the worlds biggest seller of 
office phone switches siemens could consolidate its lead if it 
manages to buy italtel an italian phone company and britains 
plessey co for which it is making a 31 billion hostile offer in 
cooperation with britains general electric co 
the price siemens is paying was not disclosed but ibm said the 
deal would have no material effect on its income statement when it 
is completed early next year that was taken as positive news for 
ibm because there had been speculation the sale price would be so 
low that ibm would be forced to take a large writeoff 
john f akers ibms chairman and chief executive said i 
would absolutely not characterize it as a scaling back of ibms 
interests in telecommunications he said the combination with 
siemens would allow ibm to offer a wider range of products to its 
customers than before 
but analysts said ibm is turning over all responsibility for 
development and manufacture of rolmbranded products to siemens and 
is discontinuing work on a complex office switch for the european 
market 
for ibm its a very clean market exit said francis 
mcinerney of northern business informationdatapro in new york 
it is a graceful but not total retreat no matter how you cut 
it said frank barbetta a researcher for probe research inc in 
cedar knolls nj 
ibm will sell the development and manufacturing arm of rolm with 
its 2800 employees to siemens it will become rolm systems inc 
and include 700 employees now working for siemens 
ibm and siemens jointly will own a marketing and services 
company known simply as rolm that will offer telecommunications 
products for private networks in the united states it will have 
5500 employees who currently work for rolm and fewer than 100 now 
working for siemens 
ibm gradually will phase out a rolm manufacturing and development 
plant in colorado springs colo and offer jobs elsewhere in the 
company to the 550 affect employees those who do not accept 
transfers will be offered severance packages 
under ibms ownership rolm has lost money steadily but its 
share of the us market has risen to 181 percent from 142 percent 
in 1984 according to northern business informationdatapro 
ibm had bought rolm as insurance in case the trend in computers 
was to connect them through office phone switches according to 
kenneth bosomworth president of international resource development 
inc of new canaan conn instead most office computers are 
connected through special local area networks an area in which ibm 
is also strong 
rolm was vulnerable to competition because it does not make 
switches for the central offices of phone companies in contrast to 
competitors such as american telephone amp telegraph co and canadas 
northern telecom ltd bosomworth said 
siemens does make central office switches phone networks are 
being redesigned to handle computer data and video signals as well 
as voice traffic and companies that make central office switches 
are at the cutting edge of work in the field bosomworth said 
in a sign of the importance the companies attached to the deal 
it was announced jointly at a news conference by akers who rarely 
appears at press conferences and karlheinz kaske president and 
chief executive of siemens 
rolm has development and manufacturing operations in santa clara 
calif and austin texas siemens has telecommunications 
development operations in boca raton fla and manufacturing in 
cherry hill nj 
the companies said rolm systems inc would be headquartered in 
santa clara and would be expanded to include about 700 siemens 
employees based in boca raton and cherry hill 
rolm the marketing company will be based in the stamford 
conn area and will include fewer than 100 people now working for 
siemens in addition to the ibm employees 
