the first fiberoptic telephone cable across the 
atlantic goes into service wednesday greatly increasing the number 
of calls that can be placed to europe at one time according to a 
published report 
the new york times in wednesdays editions says the new cable 
can carry 40000 calls simultaneously by using pulses of laser light 
to send voice and computer data 
the three existing transatlantic cables made of copper along 
with satellites can carry a total of 20000 calls the times noted 
the new cable was installed over six months at a cost of 362 
million and illustrates the increasing pace with which 
communications companies are stringing fiberoptic cables along the 
ocean floor and across north america europe asia and australia 
the cable is a joint venture of 29 european and north american 
telephone companies including american telephone amp telegraph co 
itt corp british telecommunications plc france telcom and western 
union atampt which installed the cable will also operate it 
