felony counts to avoid prosecution for racketeering and securities 
fraud the wall street journal said wednesday 
quoting sources it did not identify the newspaper said both 
sides were close to an agreement late tuesday that would end one of 
the most intensive criminal securities fraud investigations in 
history 
a 750 million fine for securities fraud would dwarf the record 
100 million in penalties paid two years ago by ivan f boesky the 
nowimprisoned stock speculator who turned states evidence and has 
been a key source of evidence against drexel 
the nations fifthlargest securities firm has maintained 
innocence throughout an investigation that has been colored by press 
leaks and speculation 
drexel executives have said they are interested in a settlement 
to avoid prosecution and a lengthy trial but admitting guilt would 
mark a stunning turnaround and open the firm to numerous civil 
lawsuits by investors who allege they were defrauded 
steven anreder drexels chief spokesman declined to comment on 
the journal story officials at the securities and exchange 
commission and manhattan us attorneys office who have been 
coordinating the drexel investigation also declined comment 
drexel is privately owned and is one of the most profitable wall 
street firms specializing in the market for highyield highrisk 
debt securities commonly called junk bonds 
it has played a major role in some of the biggest corporate 
takeovers of all time including the record 2453 billion 
acquisition of rjr nabisco inc by kohlberg kravis roberts amp co 
announced nov 30 
drexel is known to have set aside hundreds of millions of dollars 
for a potential settlement with the government the firm is eager to 
avoid a racketeering indictment which could seriously impair its 
business and involve enormous fines if a jury found drexel guilty 
three months ago sec filed a massive civil lawsuit that accused 
drexel its highyield bond financier michael milken and three other 
key employees of conspiring with boesky to profit on inside 
information manipulate stock defraud drexel clients keep phony 
books and other violations 
a federal grand jury has been expected to indict drexel on 
criminal charges as well but the indictments repeatedly have been 
delayed evidently as a pressure tactic to convince the potential 
defendants to reach pleabargain settlements instead 
while drexel has expressed interest in settling milken has not 
negotiated with government prosecutors and has vowed to vindicate 
himself at trial 
