steel imports rose 71 percent to 176 million 
tons for the first 10 months of 1988 but strong domestic demand 
held foreigners share of the market near the goal of the us quota 
program according to figures released wednesday 
over 10 months of 1988 imports accounted for 204 percent of the 
market practically the goal set by the reagan administration when 
it introduced import quotas in 1984 
imports in october declined to 15 million tons from 164 million 
tons in september and 161 million tons in october 1987 
the figures based on commerce department data were released in 
washington dc by the american iron and steel institute 
the rival american institute for imported steel said that after 
deducting 25 million tons of steel imports bought by domestic mills 
for further processing 10month imports totaled 15 million tons or 
175 percent of the market the percentage figure is well below the 
185 percent target set for finished steel products 
with quotas expiring in nine months and much being heard for 
and against renewal overriding factors in any decision in addition 
to interest of domestic steel producers must also be those of 
domestic steel users fabricators and manufacturers of 
steelintensive products whose very existence creates the market for 
both domestic steel producers and importers said erwin l klein 
president of the importers institute and vice chairman of the 
importing firm steelinter usa 
