<TEXT>
mexico is asking its creditors to reduce its 
annual foreign debt payments to the equivalent of 3 percent of its 
gross national product from the present 5 percent according to 
treasury secretary pedro aspe 
aspe told federal senators and deputies on tuesday that the new 
administration of president carlos salinas de gortari had outlined 
the proposal to creditor banks in europe and the united states 
aspe did not disclose details of the mexican proposal but the 
mexico city financial daily el financiero on wednesday said the 
proposal would nearly halve mexicos anticipated 16 billion debt 
service bill in 1989 
the mexico city newspaper el universal on wednesday reported the 
proposal won a sympathetic response from european bankers but has 
encountered obstacles and resistance in the united states because of 
the change of government there 
the newspaper said us bankers have adopted a waitandsee 
attitude toward the mexican proposal at least until presidentelect 
george bush is inaugurated on jan 20 
salinas who was sworn in dec 1 repeatedly has warned that 
mexico cannot continue to devote 5 percent of its gross national 
product each year to service its 102 billion foreign debt the 
developing worlds secondhighest after brazil 
mexico will pay an estimated 14 billion in interest and 
principal on the debt in 1988 
el financiero said aspe told a meeting of labor leaders on monday 
that salinas negotiating team wants a debt restructuring agreement 
that would target a greater proportion of mexican payments toward 
debt principal 
salinas also wants creditor banks to acknowledge the real value 
of mexican debt paper as determined by the secondary market and to 
reschedule mexicos servicing payments accordingly the newspaper 
said 
the secondary market has valued mexicos debt at 50 cents on the 
dollar 
mexico city newspapers on wednesday reported that aspe plans to 
visit washington in the next few days to take up the proposal with 
mexicos creditors 
creditor banks have balked this year on moves toward mexican 
debtreduction proposals 
mexico did reduce its debt principal by 11 billion through a 
usbacked bond auction earlier this year but the reduction was 
far less than officials originally hoped for 
aspes disclosure of the new reduction target came after salinas 
named former treasury secretary gustavo petricioli as the mexican 
ambassador to washington yet another sign of the presidents 
eagerness to achieve rapid progress in restructuring negotiations 
</TEXT>
