<TEXT>
the environmental protection agency said 
wednesday it plans to crack down on stations that sell leaded 
gasoline at far cheaper prices and allow motorists to put it in 
nolead cars 
lead disables pollution control equipment causing increases of 
up to 80 percent in emissions of pollutants the epa says 
the agency said it had written refiners and marketers warning 
that inspectors would pay close attention to stations where leaded 
gasoline is priced significantly below unleaded regular 
there are no federal penalties against individual motorists who 
use the wrong fuel but epa may impose civil fines of up to 10000 
on stations that permit it some states however make it an offense 
for individuals too 
there really isnt any excuse for pricing unleaded above 
leaded since leaded now costs more to make said richard wilson 
head of the mobile sources division in epas air pollution program 
the agency has only 20 inspectors of its own but hires an 
unspecified number through contractors these inspectors for years 
have been checking station tanks and in cooperation with local 
police deparments making spot checks of cars on the road 
those checks consistently show that one car in five has used the 
wrong fuel or had its pollution control devices tampered with at 
some time at present epa estimates that 6 percent of cars 
requiring nolead are using leaded gasoline down from more than 10 
percent a few years ago 
lead compounds have been added to gasoline since the 1920s 
because they are the cheapest antiknock additive by far until the 
1970s car engines also relied on the compounds for valve seat 
lubrication some heavy duty engines did until the mid1980s 
concern over pollution as well as lead toxicity led epa in 1985 
to order maximum permissible lead reduced by more than 90 percent 
from 11 gram per gallon to 01 gram 
this means higher refining costs to produce a given octane 
platts oilgram a trade publication on monday reported wholesale 
prices for leaded up to 2 cents a gallon higher than regular 
unleaded except in the rocky mountains and farther west where the 
two grades generally were the same 
energy department figures show leaded gasoline sold retail at 47 
cents per gallon cheaper than regular unleaded for the first nine 
months of 1988 
currently leaded gasoline is 15 percent of the market compared 
with 21 percent a year ago 
joe koach executive director of the service station dealers of 
america said epas threats to fine dealers 10000 are 
assinine 
koach complained its difficult for dealers to control 
misfueling weve had reports of dealers threatened with violence 
for trying to stop customers from buying leaded 
independent dealers he said are pressured to adhere to retail 
prices their suppliers decide on why is leaded gasoline still 
cheaper its the oil companies policy koach said 
ralph stow of amoco a major national brand that has stopped all 
leaded sales except in alcohol blends in five midwestern states 
said our dealers set their own prices 
in ashland ky dan lacy of ashland oil co a midwestern 
marketer with 2000 outlets said leaded gasoline had been priced at 
or above unleaded regular for several months now at stations his 
company serves 
the american petroleum institute the largest industry trade 
group said in a statement that misfueling was declining and would 
continue to do so and epa should ensure that both the service 
station operator and the individual motorist are prevented from 
engaging in this practice 
</TEXT>
