<TEXT>
liggett group inc announced wednesday that 
it is introducing a new cigarette called pyramid which will be 
available to retailers at carton prices comparable to those of 1980 
liggett executives say pyramid represents a new lowprice 
category that is a departure from the direction the tobacco industry 
has been taking 
cigarette prices have climbed fairly steadily since 1981 with 
the primary reason being the major excise tax increase by 
congress said hal a grant senior vice president of liggett 
group 
the difference between the price of generic cigarettes and 
fullprice cigarettes is narrowing he said and the company felt 
the time was right to establish a third tier of cigarettes 
what were going to offer smokers who are showing this clear 
preference for brandedpricevalue cigarettes is the ability to buy 
a quality product using their 1988 purchasing power at early 1980 
prices thats what the pyramid is all about grant said 
he said the savings to consumers could range from 250 to 5 per 
carton depending on the state in which it is bought or the price of 
the brand that it is being compared against 
the cigarette industry today is as competitive as it was in the 
early 1980s grant said and liggett the smallest of the six major 
cigarette manufacturers has to be innovative 
when faced with growing marketing pressures we began looking 
for nonconventional ways to counter bigspending efforts by the 
majors he said 
we cant outspend them so we try and outinnovate them with 
another new category 
the company began shipping pyramid cigarettes on monday 
